answer: @MoaadAmer You add a click event to an element. You remove that element from the page and replace it with the new one. The new one does not magically get the event that you added to that other element. So you need to either rebind the click event to the new element. Or you use event delegation (add event to a parent and the parent checks to see if the click was on a child) so the event will be attached to dynamic elements.

embedfield:
Update MongoDB Atlas collection using AWS lamda

We use MongoDB atlas, a cloud MongoDB database for our DB and NodeJS in the backend. I have to run a cron job at 2 AM every day which fetches the data from some third-party API and updates some collection in the DB. The client wants us to use AWS, preferably Lamda. Our System is run on an EC2 instance. Any leads ?? What would be the most efficient solution? It worked fine with 'node-cron' in my local but they want lamdas preferably AWS.
answer:
According to http://www.datastax.com/dev/blog/4-simple-rules-when-using-the-datastax-drivers-for-cassandra you indeed need to create one instance of `Cluster` and one for `Session` and reuse those.
Don't create a new cluster and session for every query to Cassandra

answer: The row id is most likely **nerver the same** as the ListView index. The IDs in a table start with **1**. A ListView item positions start with **0**. So you are at least *off by 1*. Not even to mention when you delete an item in the table. All the following row ids are not renumbered and new row ids will continue the count (this is so not to loose the eventual relations in other tables). You should retrieve the id in your **Adapter**.
